node.text:
No amount of money can make you love what you hate.

All they can do is pay you enough to fake.

I used to imagine a job that I’d be happy with if I made a certain amount of money. In 2018 I got a promotion that put me in a position financially to rise up and make the money I needed to make so I could be financially stress free. I was happy for a while, maybe like 2 weeks, then I became even more miserable than before.

My life was dependent upon rather or not I kept the job I had at the time, and my understanding about jobs is that companies do go out of business and when they do you go with them. That always scared me. I always stayed up late at night afraid of what would happen if I bought a nice house and a car depending on the income from a job and then all of a sudden I get fired? I never understood how that sat well with people. 

Maybe Im being extra, but It was a genuine concern, especially when the bank started letting managers go because they launched EATMs that let customers do things on their own with higher limits. Getting replaced by technology and being made obsolete was one of my biggest fears, in addition to not liking to annoying customers that came in day to day to argue about overdraft fees. I was over It. 

I started a business to get away from all the concerns and stressors of a job, and that came with It’s own set of problems, but these are problems I embraced because It meant no one could fire me. 

When you own a business you’re taking a risk. When you have a job you’re taking a risk. My advice? Do both until you can survive with just one.

A lot of people have trouble understanding this. You gotta be happy for the homies, otherwise you gonna lose em.

I never look at my friends or associates with envy because the people around me either got a hand up or we moving together. When you see someone winning, don’t try to poke holes in the circle, instead, get in.

It’s not very hard to be a winner, but it’s really easy to be a loser.

If you want to win, all you have to do is learn how to be happy for yourself and others when they have things you desire. It’s ok to want what other people have, but it’s not ok to hate them for It.

Focus on your purpose and your pace, that’s how you’ll find your peace.

It don’t matter what the next man doing, what matters is what you’re NOT doing.

I’m here to be the hand up, in case nobody in your life willing to do that for you, what I expect in return is for you to hustle and grind like your life depend on It.

node.text:
Read ⬇️ 

Yea I swim with a floatie. I can’t swim. So what 😂

Spent a week on vacation, came back, had to take care of my kids cuz they got sick, then I got sick like really sick. 

This month was a rollercoaster lol, but you know what? That’s life. So in case y’all be wondering why I haven’t been posting, it’s cuz I been recovering! 

I turned 31 on the 14th and I’ve learned so much about myself in the past year.

First thing is put your health first. I put a lot of emphasis on hustle and hard work, and very little on play. It’s been a minute since my last vacation and this one was the longest I’ve taken in a minute. It reminded me why I do what I do.

You earn money so you can buy experiences, comfort, and survive. Plain and simple.

You want to provide yourself and your family with luxury that otherwise would be inaccessible, so stop depriving yourself of a good time till “tomorrow” cuz in reality if you gotta tell yourself that over and over again then you’re probably one of the people like me that’s always working too hard and never giving yourself a break.

IT’s ok to take time off. It’s ok to relax. It’s ok to have fun. Hustle, but don’t forget why you’re hustling.

I repair phones Monday- Friday all year on Instagram live most of the time too. Tap in with me if you’d like to pick up a dope side hustle.

Hit the link in my bio to cop the free phone repair training and if you enjoy It then you’ll have the opportunity to take the full one.

Save this post!
Share with someone that works too hard.
Gimme a 💯 if you’re going to put self care first.

May be an image of text that says 'Feldon Richards @nycphonebuyer The idea that rich people got rich by cutting back on coffee, driving shitty cars, and dropping out of college is so toxic. It teaches people that if you save enough money and start a business that you'll get rich and life just don't work like that.'.

node.text:
It’s a common theme that many entrepreneurs became successful by starving themselves and eating ramen noodles and basically struggling by depriving themselves of many things.

Driving crappy cars, skipping coffee, and college. That’s just not the case.

I’m not saying these methods don’t work, but It doesn’t have to be the norm. There are plenty of ways to secure the bag without taking such drastic measures.

You don’t have to run around with your muffler dragging so you can be successful. You finance a decent car, rent It out when you’re not using It and have the payment be covered.

A cup of coffee is like $1 at McDonalds. Saving $30 a month won’t do much for your finances, in fact, It won’t do anything at all.

Areas to focus on are transportation costs, insurance, phone bill, rent, and food. Those are the areas where you’ll likely be spending the most money in. Everyone has to commute, eat, communicate, have a roof over their head and be covered in case of an emergency, so those expenses are the largest. Stay with relatives if you can!

When I first started looking for ways to bring in extra cash to help cover those expenses, I was worried about diving into hustles that were saturated. But then I realized that everything is free game because most people don’t make It past a few weeks of being consistent.

We all have something to offer. Your customers are missing something, a product or service you can give them to fill the void in their lives. Let that be the fuel that drives you forward and instead of cutting back your spending, just earn more. Someone out there needs what you’ve got, you just haven’t figured out what to give yet.

node.text:
I used to wake up and go to work just to pay my bills, I remember It like It was yesterday.

5am wake up, make breakfast, steam my suit, all while listening to a podcast in hopes that I’d come up with an idea for something better.

By 6am I’d finished eating and had to hop in the shower, then run for the train because even though my job was only 30 mins away, It took me 1.5 hours to get there. New York City.

So anyway, I’d get to work by 7:30am to start my 8am shift, and already I’m starving because, well, I had breakfast like 3 hours ago.

I’d bring snacks, but nothing holds you down like a home cooked meal.

To top It off, like we all do, I had to deal with some pretty crappy customers. But I kept smiling.

My wife is a very difficult to upset person and she taught me how to smile in the face of adversity so I used that daily. Each day id go into work and look for something to be happy about, so I could make each day better.

I’d tell myself that It could be worse, I could NOT have a job. I didn’t do that to downplay my struggle, I did It to shift my mindset. I knew I hated my job, but constantly reminding myself of It wasn’t necessary lol. It’s not like you’d forget that.

Fast forward to today. It’s 9 days before my 31st birthday and I haven’t had a job in over 2 years. Stay the course.

We run a multi millionaire dollar phone repair / reselling biz and just launched our car rental biz.

We have over 7K students all over the world that we are teaching how to get started repairing phones. I couldn’t be more grateful.

Follow @nycphonebuyer for side hustle tips

Save this post and share It with someone that needs to hear It. You’re not alone in your struggle.

node.text:
You can’t be afraid to live your life just to make someone else feel better about theirs.

Keep doing what’s best for you, even If It makes certain people not want to be next to you.

Be healthy emotionally, physically, spiritually, mentally, and financially. Don’t let anyone compromise you doing what’s best for you.

A lot of times you’ll be afraid to avoid doing something out of fear that you’ll offend people, but that’s when you must remain strong.

Say no if It means keeping yourself good, and don’t say yes just so someone else doesn’t get mad.

Prioritize you.

Start that business, regardless of how many friends and family tell you you can’t do It. That’s a healthy choice.

Lose that weight, no matter how hard people tell you it’s going to be.

Leave that toxic relationship, no matter how tough It is at the moment. You will heal. You will get better.

Share this with someone that needs to hear It, and save It so you don’t forget for yourself.

Read ⬇️:

Ok, back to my vacation. My baby is asleep on my lap as I write this and even when I made this video so my mobility is limited and you can probably see the exhaustion on my face 😂 but we are having a blast.

We’ve been going to the pool, beach, and trying new foods each day. This freedom is possible because my wife and I bet on ourselves.

Four years ago we made a decision to start a business that very few believed in, but we have a habit of being optimistic even when everyone else tries to give us reasons not to be.

I’m excited for all of you that have been following us since we started our journey, and even more excited for the ones that are just getting ready to join us now.

The training and knowledge I have to offer is like fine wine, It only gets better with time.

I teach people how to start small businesses with less than $100 fixing and flipping broken phones.

You don’t need your job, your job needs you. I’m just here to show you how and why. If you love your job, great, but even if you hate It, it’s still your responsibility to use the vehicle you have to get where you want to go.

Your job is how you save to invest in yourself, never forget that, but you don’t NEED it.

Give me a 💯 if you feel me.

Share with someone that needs to hear this.

Save this post in case you need a reminder.

Follow @nycphonebuyer to learn how to turn that 9-5 income into 24/7 income by starting your own side hustle/ business.

node.text:
No silver spoons on this end. I started right out the south Bronx next to Webster Avenue.

Did terrible in high school, straight A’s through my bachelors program in college so the past does not dictate how your future will be.

I run a multi million dollar company with almost 10 employees. 5 local and 4 overseas.

So how’d we get here?

We ran our business for 3 years operating locally out of our apartment and we kept reinvesting our profits into the business. We didn’t get greedy or side tracked and start blowing money on stuff we didn’t need.

A lot of people ask me how they can make $10k a month, and I always tell people worry about replacing your 9-5 income first. You probably only need like $2-3k as a single and $5-6k as a family depending on where you live.

Either way, if you follow the steps and make a plan then you can bounce from your 9-5 in 1-2 years. If you save up your money and invest in yourself, skys the limit.

You don’t need bank loans or good credit to start a business, you just need a plan and a mentor. So stop sulking and pick your head up. You got this.

Follow me for 💎 on side hustles. I talk about phone repair, flipping, and I’ve recently gotten into car rentals. I go live 5 days a week and some of them are saved into a series for you to rewatch.
